{"notes":"Identity UI pattern: editable chip. Shows actor name as pill in TopBar. Click → becomes text input. Blur or Enter → snaps back to chip. Placeholder 'your name' when empty. Uses local useState for editing vs display mode.

IMPLEMENTATION PLAN (ready to execute next session):

1. src/components/shared/unified-shell.tsx
   - Add import: useState (already imported)
   - Add actor state near top of component (after existing useState declarations):
     const [actor, setActor] = useState<string>(() =>
       typeof window !== 'undefined' ? (window.localStorage.getItem('bb.humanActor') ?? '') : ''
     );
   - Add useEffect to persist on change:
     useEffect(() => {
       if (typeof window !== 'undefined') window.localStorage.setItem('bb.humanActor', actor);
     }, [actor]);
   - Pass to TopBar: actor={actor} onActorChange={setActor}

2. src/components/shared/top-bar.tsx
   - Add to TopBarProps: actor?: string; onActorChange?: (name: string) => void;
   - Add editable chip component inline (no new file needed):
     - Local state: const [editing, setEditing] = useState(false);
     - When !editing: render <button onClick={() => setEditing(true)} className='...'>
         {actor || 'your name'}
       </button>
     - When editing: render <input autoFocus value={actor} onChange={e => onActorChange?.(e.target.value)}
         onBlur={() => setEditing(false)} onKeyDown={e => e.key === 'Enter' && setEditing(false)}
         placeholder='your name' className='...' />
   - Place the chip in TopBar right section, before ThemeToggle

3. Run: npm run typecheck && npm run lint && npm run test
4. Close beadboard-0fi.1 then start beadboard-0fi.2","status":"open"}
